text:
I‚Äôve been saying this for a few years now, #Solana NFT marketplaces need to rip the bandaid off and purge more than 90% of their listings. 

Take a page from the CEX playbook, make it hard to get listed, maintain listing requirements and concentrate volume.

Tokens listed:
@coinbase - 248
@binance - 402

This opens up the market for true launchpads and tier 2 exchanges to list and manage new, smaller or underperforming collections.

The problem is, everyone is trying to extract as much value and volume as possible. List everything under the premise of decentralization, meanwhile we make our fees and let bagholders become bagholders.

If the marketplace model was fundamentally overhauled it would be easier to attract and manage liquidity and proper market making activities. But the fight for marketshare and volume has left a graveyard of illiquid assets in its wake.

Until broader measures are taken, we are just throwing shit against the wall and hoping it sticks, waiting for shiny objects or sentiment to get people excited again.

text:
Want to spam Cardano with transactions like #Solana?

One mem-pool can hold 600 simple transactions. It will cost you ~$50.

#Cardano has 3000 pools, each with its own mem-pool. You must "ideally" fill all mem-pools with unique transactions.

That's 1,800,000 transactions.

It will cost you $180,000 to fill all mem-pools.

Cardano can process roughly 1,000 transactions per minute.

In about a day and a few hours, you can start filling mem-pools again.

I simplified it a bit.

Good luck!

text:
The reason why #Solana has problems is a certain form of centralization.

Let me explain. 

All blockchain networks can in principle be flooded with transactions. There is no difference between #Bitcoin, #Cardano, Solana, or #Ethereum.

The point is, that the goal of a distributed network is to remain operational and available to users even if a few nodes become suddenly unavailable for any reason.

In the case of client-server architecture, if the only available server is flooded with transactions (requests), it can become unavailable or only provide services to a limited number of users.

If all clients connect to a single server, the server represents a single point of failure.

Solana behaves similarly in that transactions are constantly pushed to leader validators. 

The network does not distinguish between transactions initiated by bots and those initiated by users. That is ok.

A problem is that all users, regardless of their geographical location or the wallets they use, may have a small chance of success in submitting a transaction when Solana is congested.

The reason is that although the validators alternate according to the schedule in the production of blocks, they are constantly flooded with new transactions from RPC nodes.

Transaction flow is directed to a single location on the network. The network is constantly creating another single point of failure for itself.

In a distributed network, there should ideally be no single point of failure. Such a network should be more resilient to transaction overload than a regular server.

Clients (users) can connect to any node in the network and submit transactions through it. Nodes should be somewhat independent from others. 

Most attempts to submit transactions should succeed as more independent nodes are involved.

However, Solana seems to create a single point of failure, which is the validators scheduled to produce the next block. It is a server-like approach.

If the current validator is congested, all users suffer. 

There is no alternative where to submit transactions to the system.

Imagine that one node is overwhelmed with valid spam transactions from bots. 

It should have minimal impact on other nodes if a sufficient number of user transactions enter the system through them. 

If a bot wanted to spam transactions to all nodes, it would have to establish a connection with all of them.

However, in the case of Solana, it is enough for the bots to spam several RPC servers.

The Solana team has implemented several network upgrades to better handle high traffic. It includes adding support for QUIC, stake-weighted QoS, and localized fee markets, etc. It did not help much.

I saw a comment that the current problem is caused by a bug in the implementation of throttling.

Throttling can help manage network traffic but it‚Äôs not a silver bullet solution. 

It is a challenge to implement throttling in a blockchain network in a way that maintains the network‚Äôs decentralization and security.

The blockchain must be decentralized. Meaning it doesn't have a central authority that can control the rate of transactions.

Implementing throttling usually requires some form of centralized control, which goes against the principle of decentralization. 

It's difficult to implement throttling in a way that is fair to all users.

That's why I think Solana has a design flaw. 

It's not just a bug that can be quickly fixed. This will only be a temporary solution and does not solve the centralization problem.

The resilience of the network must be based on the distributed nature of the blockchain.

Networks that use a mem-pool and allow nodes to pull transactions from other nodes on-demand only if there is room in their mem-pool can be more resistant to similar problems. 

Cardano is an example of this approach.

Although for some users the network may be unavailable if they submit transactions through a node that is overwhelmed with transactions, other users may not suffer from this problem at all.

If a node has a sufficient supply of transactions, it has no reason to pull (download) transactions from another node that may have spam transactions in the mem-pool.

Pull transactions on demand by nodes is a more resilient strategy than pushing transactions in one direction (and thus making a weak point).

I understand why Solana is designed this way. 

The team wanted to make a fast network. However, at the same time, the team sacrificed decentralization and security. 

In other words, Solana does not solve the blockchain trilemma.

quote.text:
There are two primary reasons why Solana may drop 75% of user transactions:

‚û°Ô∏è Transaction fees that are too cheap can lead to the network being easily overwhelmed with valid transactions, such as those attempting arbitrage. Both users and bots typically pay between $0.001 and $0.005 per transaction.

‚û°Ô∏è Solana aims to process all submitted transactions as swiftly as possible, which can result in validators being overwhelmed with transactions.

My primary focus is on the network architecture, as I believe there is a design flaw present.

Here‚Äôs an overview of a #Solana transaction‚Äôs lifecycle:

‚û°Ô∏èUsers initiate transactions through their wallet.

‚û°Ô∏èThe wallet sends the transaction to a RPC server/node. RPC servers can be run by any validator.

‚û°Ô∏èThe RPC server checks the leader schedule and forwards the transaction to the current leader as well as the next two leaders. The leader is in charge of producing a block for the current slot and is assigned four consecutive slots.

‚û°Ô∏èOnce the transaction reaches the current leader, the leader validates the transaction's signature and performs other pre-processing steps before scheduling the transaction for execution. 

See Figure 1.

Let's first explain how the validator node works.

For a transaction to be included in a block and permanently recorded in the ledger, it must traverse two underlying layers:

‚û°Ô∏è The network layer
‚û°Ô∏è The consensus layer

Initially, the transaction is processed by the network layer. If it successfully meets the validation criteria of this layer, it proceeds to the consensus layer. 

The consensus layer is tasked with determining the contents of new blocks and achieving agreement on the block across all nodes in the network.

See Figure 2.

The present issue with Solana is that transactions aren't even making it from the network layer to the consensus layer. 

The network layer is so congested (flooded by new arriving transactions) that the node opts to drop a portion of the transactions. 

A node safeguards itself from becoming overloaded and potentially crashing, which could occur due to resource depletion.

Most systems on the network behave this way.

In certain blockchains where transactions exhibit non-deterministic behavior, a transaction can pass through to the consensus layer and still fail afterward. 

The reasons for this can vary.

For instance, the conditions for executing a smart contract transaction according to the user's expectations may not be fulfilled. So the transaction is executed but fails even though the user has paid the fee.

A user transaction may fail due to being overtaken by a bot transaction.

Consider a scenario where out of 100 transactions, 10 are from users and 90 are from bots.

If a node decides to drop 30% of transactions, it is possible that all user transactions could be dropped at a given time.

If a node is overloaded, it may decide to drop even more transactions. Commonly, it is 50% of transactions.

The Solana network is operational and the computational resources of the nodes aren‚Äôt depleted due to the dropping of transactions.

As a result, there‚Äôs no need for a network restart and the risk of a node crash is low.

The main problem lies in the difficulty users face when trying to submit transactions. 

Despite the network being running, it‚Äôs essentially unusable. 

See Figure 3. Only a few bot-generated transactions get to the consensus layer. All user transactions are dropped.

It‚Äôs important to note that while each user typically has a single connection for submitting a transaction, bots can maintain multiple connections simultaneously. This gives bots a significant advantage.

Moreover, it's common for a single bot to send spam transactions to multiple nodes (via RPC servers).

This is because bots aim to have their transactions processed as quickly as possible, and sending transactions to multiple nodes increases the likelihood of this happening.

When a Solana node drops a transaction, the transaction fee is not paid. This is because the transaction fee is only incurred when a transaction is successfully processed and included in a block. 

If a transaction is dropped before it reaches the consensus layer, it is as if the transaction was never submitted, and thus no fee is charged.

In Solana, both users and bots connect to validators through RPC servers. 

These servers forward transactions to the current and next two other validators based on a pre-determined leader schedule. 

Unlike other networks that use a mem-pool, Solana transactions are sent directly as a UDP packet to the leaders of the consensus protocol. 

Solana aims to process all submitted transactions as promptly as possible. 

Instead of diffusing transactions to all nodes, which can delay their processing, transactions are directed to the next validators with the expectation that they will all be included in the next blocks.

If an RPC server fails to send a transaction to a validator, it attempts to rebroadcast it. 

The RPC nodes will continue to forward transactions to leaders every two seconds until the transaction is finalized or its block hash expires. 

If the outstanding rebroadcast queue size exceeds 10,000 transactions, new transactions are dropped to prevent the system from being overwhelmed.

For Solana nodes, the occasional overwhelming of an RPC node is not an issue. 

Dropping transactions safeguards the validators. 

However, validators can become overwhelmed by transactions, especially when multiple RPC nodes rebroadcast transactions simultaneously.

See Figure 4.

This can occur if several RPC servers try to rebroadcast transactions to the same validator (or a few of them) according to the schedule. 

Validators are particularly vulnerable to bot attacks via a limited number of RPC servers. 

In the first phase, bots flood several RPC nodes. In the second phase, all RPC nodes trying to rebroadcast transactions flood the scheduled validators.

The Solana team faces a difficult challenge. If transactions are cheap and the network tries to direct them all to several nodes at a given moment, there is always a risk of them being dropped.

Next time I will explain why #Cardano is more resistant to this problem and what is the point of distributed mem-pool.

text:
The problem with this reasoning is that you think people used #Solana and that they only want high TPS.

The reality is that many #Cardano fans prefer decentralization and would never switch to Solana. 

The same can be said about the #Bitcoin community, even though Bitcoin scales the worst of all blockchains and is not even very decentralized.

Another problem with this reasoning is that you think that the current quality and characteristics of the projects are decisive for the future. 

This is illogical thinking in the context that most projects will fundamentally develop technologically. 

There will always be people who will wait for scalability on Cardano rather than go for Solana. You underestimate the power of the community and its network effect too much. People often go where other people are.

The last problem with this reasoning is that you excessively prefer L1 scaling, while many people are fine with L2s. 

Layered architecture has certain advantages. It doesn't make sense that huge financial transactions on L1 have the same status as meaningless token airdrops. Of course, it would be nice.

Best founder. üí™ Update on #Solana load testing and spam attack fixes from @aeyakovenko 

Reminds me of my own career experience. In the valley in the 90s I was working on projects trying to evolve web 2 apps to scale using Apache webserver which was just written by Rob McCool. We fought hard to solve similar networking bottlenecks from spam HTTP requests and it was not easy. But the community cracked it and now Apache serves 23.04% of the million busiest websites. The entire internet we know came from the effort of the team that cracked this final bottleneck.  

Here we are in 2024 and #Solana and its dev community are cracking the next networking bottleneck, this time how to handle billions of spam blockchain transactions. They will crack it and the whole industry will benefit and billions of new users will come aboard. 

Software can not be tested in a closed lab environment. It has to be tested in the real world, with millions of users from all over the world on different hardware and software, different network providers and different bandwidths. We got to 1.5m concurrent users over the last weeks on Solana and discovered the next edge case bug which could never have been found without this test, aided by airdrops and memes. Network actors used massive spam attacks to game the network and block them from getting to the chain. 

The fixes are coming in, the lessons learned, the network strengthened and the next massive scaling iteration will happen, until the next edge case is hit. This is software, this is open source software, and as a software investor I am highly impressed by this team led by this founder.

Onwards. We must move value at high speed. Money velocity equals gross domestic product. These technologies will usher in the next decade of human evolution.

text:
Update on #Solana extreme load induced RPC networking issue which is in the process of being fixed.

Solana has faced the largest spike in traffic in history over the last weeks. This test has uncovered issues under high load where spam (lots of fake transactions) can be used by network participants to benefit with no consequences. By sending spam transactions participants can block other participants from accessing the chain. Therefore they have full access to the chain and others get failures. This explains the UI experience in the last 2 days during the attacks. Your requests are not even reaching Solana blockchain, they are being blocked in the RPC networking layer, specifically in the QUIC implementation, by participants throwing large numbers of transactions at the RPCs and blocking actual user requests. btw:QUIC is a protocol introduced by @Google in 2012 to enable high speed network communication. 

Note: When you are shown the high percentage of failed transaction charts, this is because user transactions are being blocked by the spammed RPCs while they transact on the blockchain. Once their spamming attack is finished user transactions resume and performance goes back to normal.

As per usual Solana and its ecosystem dev community has already found fixes that will will de-incentivize this spamming behavior. 

Remember - you can only test a software system under real load. This is part of beta testing. Without the liveness testing of this load, you cant test for these edge cases, so dont compare it to other chains or networks which have never experienced 1/10 of this volume. They are untested and will have their own edge case issues when they get there.  It is important to note this excercise will benefit all networks and they are all watching this and will implement similar controls to avoid the same issues within their particular implementation.
 
Solana validator builder @anza_xyz published a great update on this progress.

Fixes are already on the way. We are all testing blockchains in preparation for a billion users, and these tests are critical to uncover these issues before we get there.

Let the haters flood the comments and the technology investors come to my defense.
